    },
    {
      "id": "7ebf71c79edf97a884ef662224f25b30c4987f6c",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 112,
        "name": "Oleg Drokin",
        "email": "green@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "green"
      },
      "date": "2012-01-20 02:09:26.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1: I would prefer that you didn't submit this\n\n(3 inline comments)\n\nIn addition to the comments, the entire idea of static libcfs_debug_msg_data, that is not really fully static, but there is own copy for a lot of shared occurences, like every RETURN call and __CDEBUG and so on, this just strikes me as super memory wastage.\n\nAlso additionally, some places share this variable, and I can well imagine how different CPUs could pass by and fill in different details which would lead to a race on the content of the static var.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "ca9e5329af2bf77f8141d3ee5059ceac53a26ced",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2012-01-23 18:16:10.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nHongchao, please split this patch into separate patches again, so that the parts of the code Oleg doesn't object to can land to master.\n\nWe were discussing this today, and one idea from Oleg was to move libcfs_debug_msg_data into lu_env (which is unique per thread) in order to avoid races with multiple callers of the same CDEBUG message, and to avoid lots of static memory allocation.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "6f606a49d28686f97910121e5949629084fb57f1",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 119,
        "name": "Alex Zhuravlev",
        "email": "bzzz@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "bzzz"
      },
      "date": "2012-01-23 18:18:07.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nI was thinking of lu_env, but it's not everywere yet. also, I think static allocation isn't such a big deal compared to our problems with stack (especially with zfs)",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "e4b1d34feb94190f4de20497b72ee37a53d59428",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2012-02-04 08:53:56.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nAlex, I agree that having a larger module with a lot of static variables is not as bad as stack overflows, or other ugly workarounds like allocating temporary variables from the heap.\n\nOleg, the last time I looked through this code, the only potential issue with threads sharing a static variable is the risk that one thread is using a mask of e.g. D_INFO and another thread is using D_ERROR, and the error message is not printed to the console, or the info message IS printed to the console.  I think this risk is pretty small, and the number of locations where CDEBUG() is called with different masks is very small.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "aa6a37f1834ae93a88cf29e50f79bad15decd686",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 119,
        "name": "Alex Zhuravlev",
        "email": "bzzz@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "bzzz"
      },
      "date": "2012-02-06 09:31:58.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1: Looks good to me, but someone else must approve\n\nI'm still considiring the patch good enough ;)",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "c5316ead31464ac692641a9d621d6236d73c5545",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2012-02-08 00:48:14.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1: I would prefer that you didn't submit this\n\n(35 inline comments)\n\nThis patch needs some rework, but I'd like to see it included into Lustre 2.2, and potentially also Lustre 2.1.1 if it is ready soon.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "8196a8f30d011d73d548c108e5411f1c31ec1103",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 112,
        "name": "Oleg Drokin",
        "email": "green@whamcloud.com",
